				\begin{document}$$T$$\end{document} is the mean daily air temperature at 2 m height (°C) (Penman 1948). The comparison of annual and seasonal potential PET from 1981 to 2020 in the 50 meteorological stations in India is shown in Fig. 1. The evapotranspiration rate is potentially high during summer in all meteorological stations, and it ranges from 3.69 to 9.90 mm/day. Due to the tropical climate in India, the minimum value of PET observed in the meteorological stations even during the winter season is 1.79 mm/day. This highlights the need to avoid evaporation and loss of water stored for irrigation and drinking purposes in open reservoirs throughout the year.Fig. 1
Comparison of annual and seasonal potential evapotranspiration (PET) calculated by the Penman–Monteith method at the metrological stations all over India

